Because you cant add an iten on a list of type with upper bounds! You could have a List&lt;Integer extends Number&gt; or List&lt;Double extends Number&gt;, where one doesnt fit in the other for modifications operations!

    List&lt;? extends Number&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;();
    List&lt;? extends Number&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;Double&gt;();
    List&lt;? extends Number&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;Long&gt;();

In this case, the variable list could have any type in instance that extends `Number`. So you can pass it in your method, for example. But there, you don&#39;t really know which the type could be. You could have a `ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;` and saying to it add a new `Double`. In compile time makes sense, because `Double` extends `Number`, but in runtime the list could no be of this type and throw an Exception.

Just remember that, when you use the upper bounds, `&lt;? extends T&gt;`, you **can&#39;t** modify the list, just read it! There is the [Oracle tutorial][1] (see *Wildcards* chapter contents - *Upper Bounded Wildcards*, *Lower Bounded Wildcards* etc.)

  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/generics/wildcards.html

